turn.2: USS Pathfinder (AGS-1)  USS "Pathfinder" (AGS-1) was a survey vessel for the United States Navy during World War II.
turn.3: Was it used for anything else?
turn.4: Before and after the war she was USC&GSS "Pathfinder" (OSS-30) for the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey, named after the USC&GSS "Pathfinder" (1899-1941) that had surveyed and was lost in the Philippines at Corregidor.
turn.5: Are there any other interesting aspects about this article?
turn.6: " Pathfinder" ended her service 23 December 1971 as she and the Coast and Geodetic Survey itself had come the National Ocean Survey under the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA).
turn.8: "Pathfinder" was built by the Lake Washington Shipyard of Houghton, Washington with her keel laid 20 February 1941, christened by Eleanor Roosevelt Boettinger, granddaughter of the president, launched 11 January 1942 and completed 31 August 1942 with armament as a request by Navy as the ship's transfer had been approved by Department of Commerce before completion.
turn.10: The ship had been completed at a cost of $1,265,448 which was slightly under estimated costs.
